name: train production, passenger, high speed | train, passenger, high speed | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/767/documentation

Based on "train production, passenger, high speed, DE 2000". The life span of the train  is assumed to be 25 years. The yearly kilometric performance is 400'000 km resulting in a life time performance of  10’000’000 vkm. 

Service starts with the material consumption for the production of the high speed train.

This inventory calls processes of material production, representing the material composition of a ICE. For manufacturing, electricity and light oil burned in industrial furnace are included. For the transportation of materials standard distance are applied. The disposal of the high speed train is included as well.
category: C:Manufacturing/30:Manufacture of other transport equipment/302:Manufacture of railway locomotives and rolling stock/3020:Manufacture of railway locomotives and rolling stock

processDocumentation.geographyDescription: Extrapolated from "train production, passenger, high speed, DE 2000". Manufacturing data represents a train produced in Germany.
processDocumentation.technologyDescription: Mix of ICE I (40%) and ICE 2 (60%);References:;Maibach M., Peter D. and Seiler B. (1999) Ökoinventar Transporte: Grundlagen für den ökologischen Vergleich von Transportsystemen und den Einbezug von Transportsystemen in Ökobilanzen. Technischer Schlussbericht. In: Schweizerischer Nationalfonds zur Förderung der wissenschaftlichen Forschung (ed. SPP Umwelt M.). 2nd Edition. INFRAS, Zürich;von Rozycki C., Koeser H. and Schwarz H. (2003) Ecology Profile of the German High-speed Rail Passenger Transport System, ICE. In: International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, 8(2), pp. 83-91.
processDocumentation.dataTreatmentDescription: This dataset has been copied from an original dataset covering the geography DE. The uncertainty has been adjusted accordingly.
processDocumentation.samplingDescription: The data of the material composition and energy consumption is based on  literature studies.
